                    "tables": []
                }
            ],
            "correctAnswer": [
                "D"
            ],
            "solution": {
                "text": "I. Membership problem for an unrestricted \ngrammar is Undecidable. \n\nII. Given a Turing Machine M, whether L(M) is \nregular. \nNon-trivial \nproblem \nfor \nTuring \nmachine is  Undecidable. \n\n\nIII. Given two grammars G1 and G2, whether \nL(G1) = L(G2). Grammar is not given assume \nunrestricted grammar for an unrestricted \ngrammar equivalence problem is Undecidable. \n\nIV. Given an NFA N, whether there is a \ndeterministic PDA P such that N and P accept \nthe same language. Decidable",
                "images": [],
                "latex": [],
                "tables": []
            }
