            "question": {
                "text": "Let X be a recursive language and Y be a recursively \nenumerable but not recursive language. Let W and Z \nbe two languages such that Y reduces to W, and Z \nreduces to X (reduction means the standard many-\none reduction). Which one of the following \nstatements is TRUE?",
                "images": [],
                "latex": [],
                "tables": []
            },
            "options": [
                {
                    "id": "A",
                    "text": "W can be recursively enumerable and Z is \nrecursive.",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "B",
                    "text": "W can be recursive and Z is recursively \nenumerable.",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "C",
                    "text": "W is not recursively enumerable and Z is \nrecursive.",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "D",
                    "text": "W is not recursively enumerable and Z is not \nrecursive.",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                }
            ],
            "correctAnswer": [
                "C"
            ],
            "solution": {
                "text": "X: Recursive \n\nY: RE but not Recursive \n• \nY \n W\n\n\n= RE but not Recursive\nW\n\n\n= NOT RE \\le W \nSo, W can not be RE \n• \nZ\n X\n\n\n= Z\nRecursive\n\n\n= Z \\le Recursive \nSo, Z must be Recursive",
                "images": [],
                "latex": [],
                "tables": []
            }
        },
